Subject: RE: INC14184302 – Analysis of RPM Database Corruption
Hello Julien,
Following your request regarding the RPM database corruption observed during the patching operation on server S01VL9993888, we reviewed the available logs and system information to better understand the origin of the issue.
Identifying the exact root cause of an RPM database corruption can be challenging, especially after the database has been rebuilt, as the rebuild process removes temporary lock files and corruption artifacts that could help determine the exact triggering event.
Root Cause
Based on the log analysis, the RPM database errors were already present in the system logs since January 20, well before the kernel patching operation executed on March 8.
The server is running Red Hat Enterprise Linux 8, where the RPM database backend relies on Berkeley DB, which is known to be more sensitive to corruption compared to the SQLite implementation used in newer RHEL versions.
The logs contain repeated errors such as:
Copy code

rpmdb: BDB0113 Thread/process failed
BDB1507 Thread died in Berkeley DB library
DB_RUNRECOVERY: Fatal error, run database recovery
cannot open Packages database in /var/lib/rpm
rpmdb open failed
These errors indicate that the RPM database had already entered an inconsistent state prior to the patching activity. The kernel patch operation on March 8 did not cause the corruption but rather exposed the pre-existing issue when the package manager attempted to access the RPM database.
The initial corruption may have been triggered by an interrupted package transaction, concurrent access to the RPM database, or an unexpected system event during a previous package management operation.
Corrective Action
The issue was resolved by rebuilding the RPM database using the standard recovery procedure. This operation removed the corrupted temporary lock files and reconstructed the database metadata from the available package information.
After rebuilding the RPM database, the package management environment returned to a consistent state and the patching process completed successfully.
Preventive Actions
To reduce the risk of similar incidents in the future, it is recommended to perform regular health checks of the RPM database and ensure that no concurrent package management processes run during patching operations.
Additionally, performing pre-patching verification checks—such as validating RPM database accessibility, checking active package manager processes, verifying disk space availability, and ensuring dependency consistency—can help detect potential issues before patching activities.
Please let me know if additional analysis is required.
Best regards.
